{"title_page": "List of Iberian Jews", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2007}}\n\n{{Jews by country}}\n[[Jew]]s had lived in the [[Iberian peninsula]] since the Ancient Age, experiencing a [[Golden age of Jewish culture in Spain|Golden Age]] under [[Muslim]] ruple. Following the [[Reconquista]] and increasing persecution, many of them were [[Alhambra Decree|expelled from Spain]] in 1492 and [[Expulsion of the Jews from Portugal|Portugal in 1497]]. Some of their descendants, known as the [[Sephardi]]m, settled mainly in North Africa, South-East Europe, [[Sephardic Jews in the Netherlands|the Netherlands]], England, and America. Jews were only formally readmitted to the peninsula in the late 19th century. The modern Jewish Iberian population is based on post-war immigration and numbers around 14,000. The following is a list of prominent Iberian Jews arranged by country of origin:\n\n:<div class=\"boilerplate metadata\" id=\"listdev\">''This is an [[Wikipedia:Incomplete lists|incomplete list]], which may never be able to satisfy certain standards for completeness. Revisions and additions are welcome.''</div>\n\n==Portugal==\n* [[Abraham Aboab Falero]] (? - 1642), seventeenth century [[philanthropist]].\n* [[Daniel Blaufuks]] (1963 -) photographer.<ref>https://www.academia.edu/6962271/_Under_Strange_Skies_Private_and_Public_Memory_in_the_Work_of_Daniel_Blaufuks</ref>\n* [[Joshua Benoliel]] (1873 - 1932) Photojournalist, official photographer for [[Carlos I of Portugal|King Carlos I of Portugal]].<ref>https://www.newsmuseum.pt/en/imortais/joshua-benoliel</ref>\n* [[Mois\u00e9s Bensabat Amzalak]] (1892 - 1978), {{sfn|Milgram|2011|p=34}} {{cite book |last= Milgram|first=Avraham |year=2011 |title=Portugal, Salazar, and the Jews |url=|location= |publisher= Yad Vashem|pages=34 |isbn= 9789653083875 |accessdate=|ref = harv }}\n* [[Isaac Cardoso]] (1603 or 1604 - 1683) physician, philosopher, and polemic writer.<ref>https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/cardozo-cardoso-isaac</ref>\n* [[Artur Carlos de Barros Basto]] (1887 - 1961) author and military captain.<ref>https://www.timesofisrael.com/historical-drama-depicts-untold-story-of-the-1930s-portuguese-dreyfus-affair/</ref>\n* [[Artur Alberto de Campos Henriques]] (1853 - 1922) The 50th [[Prime Minister of Portugal]].{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n* [[Nico Castel]] (1931 - 2015) [[tenor]].<ref name=Fox>[[Margalit Fox|Fox, Margalit]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/04/arts/music/nico-castel-tenor-and-diction-coach-at-the-met-dies-at-83.html?hpw&rref=obituaries&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=well-region&region=bottom-well&WT.nav=bottom-well&_r=0 \"Nico Castel, Tenor and Diction Coach at the Met, Dies at 83\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 3, 2015</ref>\n* [[Uriel da Costa]] (1585 - 1640), Philosopher.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bh.org.il/blog-items/uriel-da-costa-the-story-of-a-nonbeliever/ |title=Uriel da Costa: the Story of a Nonbeliever |last=Derman |first=Ushi |date=December 19, 2018|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n* [[Abraham Curiel]] (1545-1609), physician.<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/curiel</ref>\n* [[David Curiel]] (1594-1666), merchant.<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/curiel</ref>\n* [[Jacob Curiel]] (1587-1664), diplomat, merchant and nobleman.<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/curiel</ref>\n* [[Tatiana Salem Levy]] (1979 -) Novelist.<ref>https://www.killyourdarlings.com.au/article/conversation-with-tatiana-salem-levy/</ref>\n* [[Rodrigo L\u00f3pez (physician)|Rodrigo Lopez]] (1517 \u2013 1594), physician<ref>Concise [[Dictionary of National Biography]]: \"Jewish physician\"</ref>\n* [[Fern\u00e3o de Loronha]] (1470 - 1540), Explorer and merchant.<ref><https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/noronha-loronha-fern-x00e3-o-de</ref>\n* [[Gracia Mendes Nasi]] (1510 \u2013 1569), wealthy women of Renaissance Europe, became a prominent figure in the Ottoman Empire and developed an escape network that hundreds of [[Conversos]].<ref>https://www.headstuff.org/culture/history/terrible-people-from-history/gracia-mendes-nasi-renaissance-businesswoman/</ref><ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/nasi-gracia</ref>\n* [[Solomon Molcho]] (1500 - 1532), mystic and writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishlinknj.com/features/34362-a-doomed-proposal-for-a-joint-jewish-christian-crusade-three-divergent-views-of-solomon-molcho|title=\nA Doomed Proposal for a Joint Jewish-Christian Crusade: Three Divergent Views of Solomon Molcho|work=jewishlinknj|first=Joel Davidi|last=Weisberger|date=November 14, 2018</ref>\n* [[Garcia de Orta]] (1501 - 1578) Herbalist, naturalist and physician.<ref>http://chickensoupexhibit.org/garcia-de-orta-a-portuguese-jewish-doctor/</ref>\n* [[Pedro Nunes]] (1502 - 1578), Mathematician, cosmographer, and professor<ref>http://www.dulcerodrigues.info/historia/uk/efemeride_morte_pedro_nunes_uk.html</ref>\n* [[Jacob Rodrigues Pereira]] (1715 - 1780), the first teacher of deaf-mutes in France.<ref>https://jdcc.org/feature-news/jacob-rodrigues-pereira-a-portugal-jew-in-18th-century/</ref>\n* [[Daniela Ruah]] (1983), actress, dual American citizen<ref name=\"Jewishjournal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/arts/article/film_fest_celebrates_sephardim|title=Film Fest celebrates Sephardim|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]]|first=Evan|last=Henerson|date=November 8, 2012|accessdate=March 1, 2015| archivedate=April 2, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402120151/http://www.jewishjournal.com/arts/article/film_fest_celebrates_sephardim|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Isaac Henrique Sequeira]] (1738 - 1816) Lisbon-born French doctor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elpais.com/diario/2011/04/24/cultura/1303596003_850215.html|title=Reportaje - El salvador de los 'zurbar\u00e1n'|first=Ediciones El|last=Pa\u00eds|date=24 April 2011|publisher=|accessdate=5 February 2018|via=elpais.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Prado\">{{cite web|url=https://www.museodelprado.es/en/the-collection/art-work/isaac-henrique-sequeira/8a1936f6-a7d8-4c00-b9a5-6bb1a99df911|title=Isaac Henrique Sequeira - The Collection - Museo Nacional del Prado|author=|date=|website=www.museodelprado.es|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Francisco Sanches]] (1550 \u2013 November 16, 1623), was a Portuguese born Spain raised, French skeptic philosopher and physician.\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Maria Esp\u00edrito Santo Silva Ricciardi]] (1954-), economist and banker.<ref name=\"ESIB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espiritosantoib.com/index.php?cat=8 |title=www.haitongib.com. Retrieved 2014-07-12.}}</ref>\n* [[David ben Solomon ibn Yahya]] (1425 - 1528), Rabbi sentenced by [[King Jo\u00e3o II]] to be burned at the stake fled to Corfu.<ref>https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/ibn-yahya-david-ben-solomon</ref>\n* [[Jacob Tirado]] (1540 - 1620), founder of the [[Sephardic Jews in the Netherlands|Spanish-Portuguese community of Amsterdam]].<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/tirado-jacob</ref>\n* [[Fernando Ulrich]] (1952 -), economist and banking administrator.<ref name=\"bio\">{{in lang|pt}} [https://economico.sapo.pt/noticias/fernando-ulrich-banqueiro-por-tradicao-familiar_24411.html Fernando Ulrich banqueiro por tradi\u00e7\u00e3o familiar] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520120410/http://economico.sapo.pt/noticias/fernando-ulrich-banqueiro-por-tradicao-familiar_24411.html |date=2016-05-20 }}, Econ\u00f3mico</ref>\n* [[Samuel Usque]] (1500 - 1555), author.<ref>Meyer M. A. ''Ideas of Jewish history'' 1974 p105 \"Samuel Usque (sixteenth century) was a Portuguese Marrano, a Jew forcibly converted to Christianity, who after extensive wanderings settled in Ferrara.</ref>\n* [[Richard Zimler]] (1956 -), American-born author, dual-citizen.<ref>http://goodbooksguide.blogspot.com/2009/05/writing-life-richard-zimler.html</ref><ref>https://www.thejc.com/culture/features/the-gospel-according-to-richard-zimler-demons-dreams-and-yeshua-1.486124</ref>\n\n==Spain==<!-- This section is linked from [[List of Spaniards]] -->\n\n===Pre-expulsion===\n\n* [[Petrus Alphonsi]], 11th & 12th century physician, writer, astronomer, and polemicist.<ref name=\"[[Haaretz]]\">{{cite web|title=Haaretz|url=https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/.premium-1116-great-thinker-converts-then-turns-on-jews-1.5374396|author=David B. Green|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Vidal Astori]] (15th century) merchant and silversmith.<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/murviedro</ref>\n* [[Bonafos Caballeria]] (?-1964), historian and anti-Jewish writer.\n* [[Abraham Cresques]] (1325\u20131387), cartographer.<ref name=\"The Museum of the Jewish People at Beit Hatfutsot\">{{cite web|title=You have reached your destination: The Jewish cartographers without whom we would not have WAZE|url=https://www.bh.org.il/blog-items/reached-destination-jewish-cartographers-without-not-waze/|author=Ushi Derman|accessdate=December 15, 2019</ref>\n* [[Jehud\u00e0 Cresques]] (1360\u20131410), cartographer.<ref>https://jewishreviewofbooks.com/articles/795/the-living-waters-of-history/</ref>\n* [[Alfonso de Cartagen]] (1384-1456),  Roman Catholic bishop, diplomat, historian and writer of pre-Renaissance Spain.<ref>https://brill.com/view/journals/me/24/1-3/article-p226_9.xml</ref>\n* [[Moses Hamon]] (1490-1567) physician, historian and phlanthopoist.<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/1580261?seq=1</ref>\n* [[Joseph ben Hayyim Jabez]] (15th & 16th century)  Mystic and theologian.<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jabez-joseph-ben-x1e24-ayyim</ref>\n* [[Felipe God\u00ednez]] (1588 \u2013 1637), Portuguese born dramatist of the [[Spanish Golden Age]].<ref name=\"Felipe Godinez\">{{cite web|title=Felipe Godinez|url=http://www.cervantesvirtual.com/portales/felipe_godinez/biografia/|publisher=Foundation Virtual Library Miguel de Cervantes|accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Jacob ibn Jau]] (9th century), silk-manufacturer and held a position in the court of the [[Hisham II]].<ref>https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/ibn-jau-jacob</ref>\n* [[Judah ben Joseph ibn Ezra]] (12th century), physian.<ref>https://www.britannica.com/biography/Judah-ha-Levi</ref>\n* [[Joseph Kimhi]] (1105\u20131170), rabbi and biblical commentator.<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/david-kimchi</ref>\n* [[Antonio de Le\u00f3n Pinelo]] (1589-1660) writer and historian.<ref>[https://ccjs.uchicago.edu/jewish-inka-king-paytiti-and-converso-guaman-poma-%C2%A0de-ayala-jewish-old-testament-culture-tridentine]</ref>\n* [[Moses de Le\u00f3n]] (1240-1305) rabbi and Kabbalist who is considered the composer or redactor of the Zohar. =<ref>https://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803100211684</ref>\n* [[Isaac ben Moses Eli]] (15th century), Mathematician.<ref>http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/8204-isaac-ben-moses-eli-ha-sefardi</ref> \n* [[Caterina Tarong\u00ed]] (1646-1691), burned alive by the [[Spanish Inquisition]].<ref>https://www.commentarymagazine.com/articles/a-dead-branch-on-the-tree-of-israel-the-xuetas-of-majorca/</ref>\n* [[Bartolom\u00e9 de Torres Naharro]] (1845-1530), writer.<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/338175?seq=1</ref>\n* [[Solomon ibn Verga]] (1460 \u2013 1554) historian and physician.<ref>https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/ibn-verga-solomon</ref>\n* [[Joseph Zabara]] (1140\u20131200), physicist, poet and satirist, writer of the Book of Delights'.<ref>http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/15137-zabara-joseph</ref>\n\n===Post-expulsion===\n\n* [[Isak Andic]] (1953 -), Turkish-born businessman and founder [[Mango]].<ref>https://www.businessoffashion.com/community/people/isak-andic</ref>\n* [[Miguel de Barrios]] (1625-1701), philosopher, historian and poet.<ref>https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/barrios-daniel-levi-miguel-de</ref><ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/1453280</ref>\n* [[Nissan Ben-Avraham]] (1957-), Marrano rabbi.<ref name=JPmore>{{Cite news|publisher=[[Jerusalem Post]]|title=First ex-Marrano Israeli rabbi returns to Spain as emissary|date=Dec 15, 2019|url=http://www.jpost.com/JewishWorld/JewishNews/Article.aspx?id=168149}}</ref>\n* [[Esther Bendahan]] (1964 -),  Moroccan born author.<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/43744033?seq=1</ref>\n* [[Elena Benarroch]] (1955 -), fashion designer.<ref>https://www.levante-emv.com/vida-y-estilo/gente/personajes/2013/10/17/elena-benarroch-perfecta-jewish-mama/1042475.html</ref><ref>https://www.jta.org/2002/11/25/archive/around-the-jewish-world-few-jews-in-spain-yet-supposed-jewish-lobby-still-draws-readers</ref>\n* {{ill|El\u00edas Bendodo|es}} (1974 -), politician, former President of Malaga Provincial Deputation\n* [[Doris Benegas]] (1951-2016), Venezuelan-born political lawyer, half Jewish.<ref>https://www.elmundo.es/suplementos/cronica/2009/709/1242511206.html</ref>\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Benegas]] (1948-2015), Venezuelan-born politician for the [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]], half Jewish.<ref>https://www.elmundo.es/suplementos/cronica/2009/709/1242511206.html</ref>\n* [[Ricardo Bofill]] (1939 -) World famous architect, half Jewish.<ref name=\"World-Architects\">{{cite web|url=https://www.world-architects.com/en/architecture-news/insight/versailles-for-the-people|title= Versailles for the People |work=World-Architects.com|first=Ulf|last=Meyer|date=December 5, 2019|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Rafael Cansinos-Ass\u00e9ns]] (1882-1964)  poet, novelist, essayist, literary critic and translator.<ref name=\"Jewishquarterly\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishquarterly.org/2009/05/a-catalogue-of-jewish-symbols-by-ilan-stavans/|title=A Catalogue of Jewish Symbols |work=[[Jewishquarterly]]|first=Ilan|last=Stavans|date=August 24, 2014|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Abraham Miguel Cardoso]] (1626\u20131706), Sabbatean prophet and physician.<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/1486734?seq=1</ref>\n* [[Isaac Carasso]] (1874 \u2013 1939), [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] born co-founder of [[Danone]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071015040444/http://www.public-histoire.com/saga/yaourt/yaourt7.html]</ref>\n* [[Daniel Carasso]] (1905 - 2009), [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] born co-founder of [[Danone]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071015040444/http://www.public-histoire.com/saga/yaourt/yaourt7.html]</ref>\n* [[Pancracio Celdr\u00e1n]] (1942-2019), Professor, intellectual and journalist who specializes in history & literature of antiquity & the medieval period.\n* [[Claudio Guill\u00e9n]] (1924-2007), French-born writer and historian, half Jewish.<ref>https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2011/02/claudio-guillen/</ref>\n* [[Heinrich G\u00e4rtner]] (1885-1962) [[Austro-Hungarian Empire|Austro-Hungarian]]-born cinematographer.<ref>Bock & Bergfelder p.572</ref>\n* [[Andr\u00e9s Herzog]] (1974 -), Politician and lawyer that is the spokesperson of the [[Union, Progress and Democracy]] (UPyD),half Jewish.<ref>https://elpais.com/politica/2015/07/22/actualidad/1437566420_809835.html</ref>\n* [[Jon Juaristi]] (1951 -) poet, essayist and translator, as a self-confessed former ETA militant. Convert.<ref name=\"[[Politika]]\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politika.io/en/notice/basques-jews-and-the-racialization-of-spanish-identity |title=Basques, Jews, and the Racialization of Spanish Identity|first=Jean-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|last=Schaub|date=February 26, 2018|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Alicia Koplowitz]] (1954 -), businesswoman and philanthropist, half Jewish.<ref name=ABCMasRicas>[http://www.abc.es/hemeroteca/historico-24-08-2007/abc/Gente/las-koplowitz-las-mas-ricas-de-espa%C3%B1a_164500293074.html ABC (Spain): \"Las Koplowitz Las m\u00e1s ricas de Espa\u00f1a\" by ISABEL GUTI\u00c9RREZ (''in Spanish'')] August 24, 2007</ref><ref name=ABCMasRicas />\n* [[Esther Koplowitz]] (1953 -), businesswoman and philanthropist,half Jewish.<ref name=ABCMasRicas>[http://www.abc.es/hemeroteca/historico-24-08-2007/abc/Gente/las-koplowitz-las-mas-ricas-de-espa%C3%B1a_164500293074.html ABC (Spain): \"Las Koplowitz Las m\u00e1s ricas de Espa\u00f1a\" by ISABEL GUTI\u00c9RREZ (''in Spanish'')] August 24, 2007</ref><ref name=ABCMasRicas />\n* [[Enrique M\u00fagica Herzog]] (1932 -) a lawyer, politician and co-founder of [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]], half-Jewish.<ref>[https://www.jta.org/1988/07/12/archive/minister-in-spanish-government-first-jew-since-inquisition]</ref><ref>https://www.haaretz.com/1.4955014</ref>\n* [[Romeo Niram]] (1974- ), figurative painter.\n* [[Eduardo Propper de Callej\u00f3n]] (1895 - 1972), diplomat remembered for facilitating escape of tens of thousands of Jews from France, half Jewish.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n* [[Antonio Puerta]] (1984-2007) footballer.<ref>[https://headbandsandheartbreak.wordpress.com/2012/08/28/sergio-remembers-antonio-puerta-on-his-yahrzeit/]</ref>\n* [[Samuel Toledano]] (1929-1996) Moroccan-born Jewish lawyer and Jewish community leader.<ref name=\"[[New York Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/07/25/world/samuel-toledano-66-advocate-for-jews-of-spain.html|title=Samuel Toledano 66 advocate for jews of spain|work=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Joseph de la Vega]] (1650-1692), well known merchant, poet, and philanthropist in Amsterdam.<ref>{{cite web|title=The First Book Written About a Stock Market Is Selling for $300,000|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-12-04/the-first-book-written-about-a-stock-market-is-selling-for-300-000|author= James Tarmy|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Sephardic Jews]]\n*[[Sephardi Jews]]\n*[[History of the Jews in Spain]]\n*[[Spanish and Portuguese Jews]]\n*[[Lists of Jews]]\n*[[List of Portuguese]]\n*[[List of Spaniards]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Iberian Jews}}\n[[Category:Lists of Jews|Iberian Jews]]\n[[Category:Lists of Jews by country|Iberian Jews]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Jews| ]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews| ]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews topics| ]]\n[[Category:Spanish Jews| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of Spanish people|Jews]]\n[[Category:Lists of Portuguese people]]\n[[Category:Lists of people by ethnicity|Jews]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\n{{Refimprove|date=January 2007}}\n\n{{Jews by country}}\n[[Jew]]s had lived in the [[Iberian peninsula]] since the Ancient Age, experiencing a [[Golden age of Jewish culture in Spain|Golden Age]] under [[Muslim]] ruple. Following the [[Reconquista]] and increasing persecution, many of them were [[Alhambra Decree|expelled from Spain]] in 1492 and [[Expulsion of the Jews from Portugal|Portugal in 1497]]. Some of their descendants, known as the [[Sephardi]]m, settled mainly in North Africa, South-East Europe, [[Sephardic Jews in the Netherlands|the Netherlands]], England, and America. Jews were only formally readmitted to the peninsula in the late 19th century. The modern Jewish Iberian population is based on post-war immigration and numbers around 14,000. The following is a list of prominent Iberian Jews arranged by country of origin:\n\n:<div class=\"boilerplate metadata\" id=\"listdev\">''This is an [[Wikipedia:Incomplete lists|incomplete list]], which may never be able to satisfy certain standards for completeness. Revisions and additions are welcome.''</div>\n\n==Portugal==\n* [[Abraham Aboab Falero]] (? - 1642), seventeenth century [[philanthropist]].\n* [[Daniel Blaufuks]] (1963 -) photographer.<ref>https://www.academia.edu/6962271/_Under_Strange_Skies_Private_and_Public_Memory_in_the_Work_of_Daniel_Blaufuks</ref>\n* [[Joshua Benoliel]] (1873 - 1932) Photojournalist, official photographer for [[Carlos I of Portugal|King Carlos I of Portugal]].<ref>https://www.newsmuseum.pt/en/imortais/joshua-benoliel</ref>\n* [[Mois\u00e9s Bensabat Amzalak]] (1892 - 1978), {{sfn|Milgram|2011|p=34}} {{cite book |last= Milgram|first=Avraham |year=2011 |title=Portugal, Salazar, and the Jews |url=|location= |publisher= Yad Vashem|pages=34 |isbn= 9789653083875 |accessdate=|ref = harv }}\n* [[Isaac Cardoso]] (1603 or 1604 - 1683) physician, philosopher, and polemic writer.<ref>https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/cardozo-cardoso-isaac</ref>\n* [[Artur Carlos de Barros Basto]] (1887 - 1961) author and military captain.<ref>https://www.timesofisrael.com/historical-drama-depicts-untold-story-of-the-1930s-portuguese-dreyfus-affair/</ref>\n* [[Artur Alberto de Campos Henriques]] (1853 - 1922) The 50th [[Prime Minister of Portugal]].{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n* [[Nico Castel]] (1931 - 2015) [[tenor]].<ref name=Fox>[[Margalit Fox|Fox, Margalit]]. [https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/04/arts/music/nico-castel-tenor-and-diction-coach-at-the-met-dies-at-83.html?hpw&rref=obituaries&action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=well-region&region=bottom-well&WT.nav=bottom-well&_r=0 \"Nico Castel, Tenor and Diction Coach at the Met, Dies at 83\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', June 3, 2015</ref>\n* [[Uriel da Costa]] (1585 - 1640), Philosopher.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bh.org.il/blog-items/uriel-da-costa-the-story-of-a-nonbeliever/ |title=Uriel da Costa: the Story of a Nonbeliever |last=Derman |first=Ushi |date=December 19, 2018|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref>\n* [[Abraham Curiel]] (1545-1609), physician.<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/curiel</ref>\n* [[David Curiel]] (1594-1666), merchant.<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/curiel</ref>\n* [[Jacob Curiel]] (1587-1664), diplomat, merchant and nobleman.<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/curiel</ref>\n* [[Tatiana Salem Levy]] (1979 -) Novelist.<ref>https://www.killyourdarlings.com.au/article/conversation-with-tatiana-salem-levy/</ref>\n* [[Rodrigo L\u00f3pez (physician)|Rodrigo Lopez]] (1517 \u2013 1594), physician<ref>Concise [[Dictionary of National Biography]]: \"Jewish physician\"</ref>\n* [[Fern\u00e3o de Loronha]] (1470 - 1540), Explorer and merchant.<ref><https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/noronha-loronha-fern-x00e3-o-de</ref>\n* [[Gracia Mendes Nasi]] (1510 \u2013 1569), wealthy women of Renaissance Europe, became a prominent figure in the Ottoman Empire and developed an escape network that hundreds of [[Conversos]].<ref>https://www.headstuff.org/culture/history/terrible-people-from-history/gracia-mendes-nasi-renaissance-businesswoman/</ref><ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/nasi-gracia</ref>\n* [[Solomon Molcho]] (1500 - 1532), mystic and writer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishlinknj.com/features/34362-a-doomed-proposal-for-a-joint-jewish-christian-crusade-three-divergent-views-of-solomon-molcho|title=\nA Doomed Proposal for a Joint Jewish-Christian Crusade: Three Divergent Views of Solomon Molcho|work=jewishlinknj|first=Joel Davidi|last=Weisberger|date=November 14, 2018</ref>\n* [[Garcia de Orta]] (1501 - 1578) Herbalist, naturalist and physician.<ref>http://chickensoupexhibit.org/garcia-de-orta-a-portuguese-jewish-doctor/</ref>\n* [[Pedro Nunes]] (1502 - 1578), Mathematician, cosmographer, and professor<ref>http://www.dulcerodrigues.info/historia/uk/efemeride_morte_pedro_nunes_uk.html</ref>\n* [[Jacob Rodrigues Pereira]] (1715 - 1780), the first teacher of deaf-mutes in France.<ref>https://jdcc.org/feature-news/jacob-rodrigues-pereira-a-portugal-jew-in-18th-century/</ref>\n* [[Daniela Ruah]] (1983), actress, dual American citizen<ref name=\"Jewishjournal\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/arts/article/film_fest_celebrates_sephardim|title=Film Fest celebrates Sephardim|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]]|first=Evan|last=Henerson|date=November 8, 2012|accessdate=March 1, 2015| archivedate=April 2, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402120151/http://www.jewishjournal.com/arts/article/film_fest_celebrates_sephardim|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Isaac Henrique Sequeira]] (1738 - 1816) Lisbon-born French doctor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elpais.com/diario/2011/04/24/cultura/1303596003_850215.html|title=Reportaje - El salvador de los 'zurbar\u00e1n'|first=Ediciones El|last=Pa\u00eds|date=24 April 2011|publisher=|accessdate=5 February 2018|via=elpais.com}}</ref><ref name=\"Prado\">{{cite web|url=https://www.museodelprado.es/en/the-collection/art-work/isaac-henrique-sequeira/8a1936f6-a7d8-4c00-b9a5-6bb1a99df911|title=Isaac Henrique Sequeira - The Collection - Museo Nacional del Prado|author=|date=|website=www.museodelprado.es|accessdate=5 February 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Francisco Sanches]] (1550 \u2013 November 16, 1623), was a Portuguese born Spain raised, French skeptic philosopher and physician.\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Maria Esp\u00edrito Santo Silva Ricciardi]] (1954-), economist and banker.<ref name=\"ESIB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.espiritosantoib.com/index.php?cat=8 |title=www.haitongib.com. Retrieved 2014-07-12.}}</ref>\n* [[David ben Solomon ibn Yahya]] (1425 - 1528), Rabbi sentenced by [[King Jo\u00e3o II]] to be burned at the stake fled to Corfu.<ref>https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/ibn-yahya-david-ben-solomon</ref>\n* [[Jacob Tirado]] (1540 - 1620), founder of the [[Sephardic Jews in the Netherlands|Spanish-Portuguese community of Amsterdam]].<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/tirado-jacob</ref>\n* [[Fernando Ulrich]] (1952 -), economist and banking administrator.<ref name=\"bio\">{{in lang|pt}} [https://economico.sapo.pt/noticias/fernando-ulrich-banqueiro-por-tradicao-familiar_24411.html Fernando Ulrich banqueiro por tradi\u00e7\u00e3o familiar] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160520120410/http://economico.sapo.pt/noticias/fernando-ulrich-banqueiro-por-tradicao-familiar_24411.html |date=2016-05-20 }}, Econ\u00f3mico</ref>\n* [[Samuel Usque]] (1500 - 1555), author.<ref>Meyer M. A. ''Ideas of Jewish history'' 1974 p105 \"Samuel Usque (sixteenth century) was a Portuguese Marrano, a Jew forcibly converted to Christianity, who after extensive wanderings settled in Ferrara.</ref>\n* [[Richard Zimler]] (1956 -), American-born author, dual-citizen.<ref>http://goodbooksguide.blogspot.com/2009/05/writing-life-richard-zimler.html</ref><ref>https://www.thejc.com/culture/features/the-gospel-according-to-richard-zimler-demons-dreams-and-yeshua-1.486124</ref>\n\n==Spain==<!-- This section is linked from [[List of Spaniards]] -->\n\n===Pre-expulsion===\n\n* [[Petrus Alphonsi]], 11th & 12th century physician, writer, astronomer, and polemicist.<ref name=\"[[Haaretz]]\">{{cite web|title=Haaretz|url=https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/.premium-1116-great-thinker-converts-then-turns-on-jews-1.5374396|author=David B. Green|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Vidal Astori]] (15th century) merchant and silversmith.<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/murviedro</ref>\n* [[Bonafos Caballeria]] (?-1964), historian and anti-Jewish writer.\n* [[Abraham Cresques]] (1325\u20131387), cartographer.<ref name=\"The Museum of the Jewish People at Beit Hatfutsot\">{{cite web|title=You have reached your destination: The Jewish cartographers without whom we would not have WAZE|url=https://www.bh.org.il/blog-items/reached-destination-jewish-cartographers-without-not-waze/|author=Ushi Derman|accessdate=December 15, 2019</ref>\n* [[Jehud\u00e0 Cresques]] (1360\u20131410), cartographer.<ref>https://jewishreviewofbooks.com/articles/795/the-living-waters-of-history/</ref>\n* [[Alfonso de Cartagen]] (1384-1456),  Roman Catholic bishop, diplomat, historian and writer of pre-Renaissance Spain.<ref>https://brill.com/view/journals/me/24/1-3/article-p226_9.xml</ref>\n* [[Moses Hamon]] (1490-1567) physician, historian and phlanthopoist.<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/1580261?seq=1</ref>\n* [[Joseph ben Hayyim Jabez]] (15th & 16th century)  Mystic and theologian.<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jabez-joseph-ben-x1e24-ayyim</ref>\n* [[Felipe God\u00ednez]] (1588 \u2013 1637), Portuguese born dramatist of the [[Spanish Golden Age]].<ref name=\"Felipe Godinez\">{{cite web|title=Felipe Godinez|url=http://www.cervantesvirtual.com/portales/felipe_godinez/biografia/|publisher=Foundation Virtual Library Miguel de Cervantes|accessdate=4 November 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Jacob ibn Jau]] (9th century), silk-manufacturer and held a position in the court of the [[Hisham II]].<ref>https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/ibn-jau-jacob</ref>\n* [[Judah ben Joseph ibn Ezra]] (12th century), physian.<ref>https://www.britannica.com/biography/Judah-ha-Levi</ref>\n* [[Joseph Kimhi]] (1105\u20131170), rabbi and biblical commentator.<ref>https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/david-kimchi</ref>\n* [[Antonio de Le\u00f3n Pinelo]] (1589-1660) writer and historian.<ref>[https://ccjs.uchicago.edu/jewish-inka-king-paytiti-and-converso-guaman-poma-%C2%A0de-ayala-jewish-old-testament-culture-tridentine]</ref>\n* [[Moses de Le\u00f3n]] (1240-1305) rabbi and Kabbalist who is considered the composer or redactor of the Zohar. =<ref>https://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/oi/authority.20110803100211684</ref>\n* [[Isaac ben Moses Eli]] (15th century), Mathematician.<ref>http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/8204-isaac-ben-moses-eli-ha-sefardi</ref> \n* [[Caterina Tarong\u00ed]] (1646-1691), burned alive by the [[Spanish Inquisition]].<ref>https://www.commentarymagazine.com/articles/a-dead-branch-on-the-tree-of-israel-the-xuetas-of-majorca/</ref>\n* [[Bartolom\u00e9 de Torres Naharro]] (1845-1530), writer.<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/338175?seq=1</ref>\n* [[Solomon ibn Verga]] (1460 \u2013 1554) historian and physician.<ref>https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/ibn-verga-solomon</ref>\n* [[Joseph Zabara]] (1140\u20131200), physicist, poet and satirist, writer of the Book of Delights'.<ref>http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/15137-zabara-joseph</ref>\n\n===Post-expulsion===\n\n* [[Isak Andic]] (1953 -), Turkish-born businessman and founder [[Mango]].<ref>https://www.businessoffashion.com/community/people/isak-andic</ref>\n* [[Miguel de Barrios]] (1625-1701), philosopher, historian and poet.<ref>https://www.encyclopedia.com/religion/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/barrios-daniel-levi-miguel-de</ref><ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/1453280</ref>\n* [[Nissan Ben-Avraham]] (1957-), Marrano rabbi.<ref name=JPmore>{{Cite news|publisher=[[Jerusalem Post]]|title=First ex-Marrano Israeli rabbi returns to Spain as emissary|date=Dec 15, 2019|url=http://www.jpost.com/JewishWorld/JewishNews/Article.aspx?id=168149}}</ref>\n* [[Esther Bendahan]] (1964 -),  Moroccan born author.<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/43744033?seq=1</ref>\n* [[Elena Benarroch]] (1955 -), fashion designer.<ref>https://www.levante-emv.com/vida-y-estilo/gente/personajes/2013/10/17/elena-benarroch-perfecta-jewish-mama/1042475.html</ref><ref>https://www.jta.org/2002/11/25/archive/around-the-jewish-world-few-jews-in-spain-yet-supposed-jewish-lobby-still-draws-readers</ref>\n* [[Doris Benegas]] (1951-2016), Venezuelan-born political lawyer, half Jewish.<ref>https://www.elmundo.es/suplementos/cronica/2009/709/1242511206.html</ref>\n* [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Benegas]] (1948-2015), Venezuelan-born politician for the [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]], half Jewish.<ref>https://www.elmundo.es/suplementos/cronica/2009/709/1242511206.html</ref>\n* [[Ricardo Bofill]] (1939 -) World famous architect, half Jewish.<ref name=\"World-Architects\">{{cite web|url=https://www.world-architects.com/en/architecture-news/insight/versailles-for-the-people|title= Versailles for the People |work=World-Architects.com|first=Ulf|last=Meyer|date=December 5, 2019|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Rafael Cansinos-Ass\u00e9ns]] (1882-1964)  poet, novelist, essayist, literary critic and translator.<ref name=\"Jewishquarterly\">{{cite web|url=https://www.jewishquarterly.org/2009/05/a-catalogue-of-jewish-symbols-by-ilan-stavans/|title=A Catalogue of Jewish Symbols |work=[[Jewishquarterly]]|first=Ilan|last=Stavans|date=August 24, 2014|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Abraham Miguel Cardoso]] (1626\u20131706), Sabbatean prophet and physician.<ref>https://www.jstor.org/stable/1486734?seq=1</ref>\n* [[Isaac Carasso]] (1874 \u2013 1939), [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] born co-founder of [[Danone]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071015040444/http://www.public-histoire.com/saga/yaourt/yaourt7.html]</ref>\n* [[Daniel Carasso]] (1905 - 2009), [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] born co-founder of [[Danone]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071015040444/http://www.public-histoire.com/saga/yaourt/yaourt7.html]</ref>\n* [[Pancracio Celdr\u00e1n]] (1942-2019), Professor, intellectual and journalist who specializes in history & literature of antiquity & the medieval period.\n* [[Claudio Guill\u00e9n]] (1924-2007), French-born writer and historian, half Jewish.<ref>https://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2011/02/claudio-guillen/</ref>\n* [[Heinrich G\u00e4rtner]] (1885-1962) [[Austro-Hungarian Empire|Austro-Hungarian]]-born cinematographer.<ref>Bock & Bergfelder p.572</ref>\n* [[Andr\u00e9s Herzog]] (1974 -), Politician and lawyer that is the spokesperson of the [[Union, Progress and Democracy]] (UPyD),half Jewish.<ref>https://elpais.com/politica/2015/07/22/actualidad/1437566420_809835.html</ref>\n* [[Jon Juaristi]] (1951 -) poet, essayist and translator, as a self-confessed former ETA militant. Convert.<ref name=\"[[Politika]]\">{{cite web|url=https://www.politika.io/en/notice/basques-jews-and-the-racialization-of-spanish-identity |title=Basques, Jews, and the Racialization of Spanish Identity|first=Jean-Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|last=Schaub|date=February 26, 2018|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Alicia Koplowitz]] (1954 -), businesswoman and philanthropist, half Jewish.<ref name=ABCMasRicas>[http://www.abc.es/hemeroteca/historico-24-08-2007/abc/Gente/las-koplowitz-las-mas-ricas-de-espa%C3%B1a_164500293074.html ABC (Spain): \"Las Koplowitz Las m\u00e1s ricas de Espa\u00f1a\" by ISABEL GUTI\u00c9RREZ (''in Spanish'')] August 24, 2007</ref><ref name=ABCMasRicas />\n* [[Esther Koplowitz]] (1953 -), businesswoman and philanthropist,half Jewish.<ref name=ABCMasRicas>[http://www.abc.es/hemeroteca/historico-24-08-2007/abc/Gente/las-koplowitz-las-mas-ricas-de-espa%C3%B1a_164500293074.html ABC (Spain): \"Las Koplowitz Las m\u00e1s ricas de Espa\u00f1a\" by ISABEL GUTI\u00c9RREZ (''in Spanish'')] August 24, 2007</ref><ref name=ABCMasRicas />\n* [[Enrique M\u00fagica Herzog]] (1932 -) a lawyer, politician and co-founder of [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party]], half-Jewish.<ref>[https://www.jta.org/1988/07/12/archive/minister-in-spanish-government-first-jew-since-inquisition]</ref><ref>https://www.haaretz.com/1.4955014</ref>\n* [[Romeo Niram]] (1974- ), figurative painter.\n* [[Eduardo Propper de Callej\u00f3n]] (1895 - 1972), diplomat remembered for facilitating escape of tens of thousands of Jews from France, half Jewish.{{cn|date=December 2019}}\n* [[Antonio Puerta]] (1984-2007) footballer.<ref>[https://headbandsandheartbreak.wordpress.com/2012/08/28/sergio-remembers-antonio-puerta-on-his-yahrzeit/]</ref>\n* [[Samuel Toledano]] (1929-1996) Moroccan-born Jewish lawyer and Jewish community leader.<ref name=\"[[New York Times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/07/25/world/samuel-toledano-66-advocate-for-jews-of-spain.html|title=Samuel Toledano 66 advocate for jews of spain|work=[[New York Times]]|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Joseph de la Vega]] (1650-1692), well known merchant, poet, and philanthropist in Amsterdam.<ref>{{cite web|title=The First Book Written About a Stock Market Is Selling for $300,000|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-12-04/the-first-book-written-about-a-stock-market-is-selling-for-300-000|author= James Tarmy|accessdate=December 15, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Sephardic Jews]]\n*[[Sephardi Jews]]\n*[[History of the Jews in Spain]]\n*[[Spanish and Portuguese Jews]]\n*[[Lists of Jews]]\n*[[List of Portuguese]]\n*[[List of Spaniards]]\n\n==Notes==\n<references/>\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of Iberian Jews}}\n[[Category:Lists of Jews|Iberian Jews]]\n[[Category:Lists of Jews by country|Iberian Jews]]\n[[Category:Portuguese Jews| ]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews| ]]\n[[Category:Sephardi Jews topics| ]]\n[[Category:Spanish Jews| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of Spanish people|Jews]]\n[[Category:Lists of Portuguese people]]\n[[Category:Lists of people by ethnicity|Jews]]\n", "name_user": "Sinaloa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePost-expulsion", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Iberian_Jews"}
{"title_page": "Brigitte Liso", "text_new": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n| name        = Brigitte Liso\n| office      = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br />for [[Nord's 4th constituency]]\n| term_start  = 21 June 2017\n| term_end    =\n| predecessor = [[Marc-Philippe Daubresse]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1959|07|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Lille]], France\n| nationality = French\n| party       = [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]]\n}}\n'''Brigitte Liso''' (born 29 July 1959) is a French politician representing [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] (LREM) who was elected to the [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]] on 18 June 2017, representing the [[Departments of France|department]] of [[Nord (French department)|Nord]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/legislatives-2017/059/05904.html |title=Elections l\u00e9gislatives 2017 |accessdate=19 June 2017 |work=Ministry of the Interior |language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nLiso spent her career in the private sector as a public and commercial relations manager for major groups such as [[Pernod Ricard]] and [[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette Livre]], then as a medical sales representative for [[GlaxoSmithKline]].<ref>Lucie Alexandre (June 220, 2018), [https://www.la-croix.com/France/Politique/deputes-LREM-Brigitte-Liso-Thomas-Mesnier-racontent-lAssemblee-2018-06-22-1200949293 Les d\u00e9put\u00e9s LREM Brigitte Liso et Thomas Mesnier racontent un an \u00e0 l\u2019Assembl\u00e9e]\u00a0''[[La Croix]]''.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn parliament, Lisso served on the Committee on Cultural Affairs and Education from 2017 until 2019 before moving to the Committee on Foreign Affairs. In addition to her committee assignments, she is part of the French-Italian Parliamentary Friendship Group.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA720446 Brigitte Liso] Assembl\u00e9e Nationale.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2017 French legislative election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liso, Brigitte}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 15th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:La R\u00e9publique En Marche politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Lille]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (France)]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Hauts-de-France]]\n\n\n{{France-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|French politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n| name        = Brigitte Liso\n| office      = Member of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]]<br />for [[Nord's 4th constituency]]\n| term_start  = 21 June 2017\n| term_end    =\n| predecessor = [[Marc-Philippe Daubresse]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1959|07|29|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Lille]], France\n| nationality = French\n| party       = [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]]\n}}\n'''Brigitte Liso''' (born 29 July 1959) is a French politician representing [[La R\u00e9publique En Marche!]] (LREM) who was elected to the [[National Assembly (France)|French National Assembly]] on 18 June 2017, representing the [[Departments of France|department]] of [[Nord (French department)|Nord]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{Cite web|url=http://elections.interieur.gouv.fr/legislatives-2017/059/05904.html |title=Elections l\u00e9gislatives 2017 |accessdate=19 June 2017 |work=Ministry of the Interior |language=French}}</ref>\n\n==Early career==\nLiso spent her career in the private sector as a public and commercial relations manager for major groups such as [[Pernod Ricard]] and [[Hachette (publisher)|Hachette Livre]], then as a medical sales representative for [[GlaxoSmithKline]].<ref>Lucie Alexandre (June 220, 2018), [https://www.la-croix.com/France/Politique/deputes-LREM-Brigitte-Liso-Thomas-Mesnier-racontent-lAssemblee-2018-06-22-1200949293 Les d\u00e9put\u00e9s LREM Brigitte Liso et Thomas Mesnier racontent un an \u00e0 l\u2019Assembl\u00e9e]\u00a0''[[La Croix]]''.</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn parliament, Lisso served on the Committee on Cultural Affairs and Education from 2017 until 2019 before moving to the Committee on Foreign Affairs. In addition to her committee assignments, she is part of the French-Italian Parliamentary Friendship Group.<ref>[http://www2.assemblee-nationale.fr/deputes/fiche/OMC_PA720446 Brigitte Liso] Assembl\u00e9e Nationale.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2017 French legislative election]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liso, Brigitte}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 15th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:La R\u00e9publique En Marche politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women politicians]]\n[[Category:People from Lille]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (France)]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Hauts-de-France]]\n\n\n{{France-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brigitte_Liso"}
{"title_page": "Brokenhearted (Karmin song)", "text_new": "{{short description|2012 Single by Karmin}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Brokenhearted\n| cover      = Karmin-Brokenhearted-single-cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Karmin]]\n| album      = [[Hello (Karmin album)|Hello]]\n| released   = February 7, 2012\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   = 2011\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Pop music|Pop]], [[Dance music|dance]], [[pop rap]], [[hip hop]], [[synthpop]]\n| length     = 3:50\n| label      = [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|Amy Heidemann|Nick Noonan|[[John Hill (producer)|John Hill]]|[[Claude Kelly]]|Henry Walter|[[Benny Blanco]]|[[Emily Wright (songwriter)|Emily Wright]]|Richard Head}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|Benny Blanco|[[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]]|Emily Wright}}\n| prev_title = [[Crash Your Party]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[Hello (Karmin song)|Hello]]\n| next_year  = 2012\n}}\n\"'''Brokenhearted'''\" is a song by American [[pop music|pop]] duo [[Karmin]]. It was released as the lead single from their debut EP, ''[[Hello (Karmin EP)|Hello]]'' (2012). It was written by band members Amy Heidemann and Nick Noonan, [[Claude Kelly]], [[Benny Blanco]], [[Emily Wright (songwriter)|Emily Wright]], Henry Walter, [[John Hill (producer)|John Hill]] and Richard Head, and produced by Benny Blanco, [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]] and Emily Wright.<ref>{{cite web|title=BMI: Brokenhearted Songwriters|url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/title.asp?blnWriter=True&blnPublisher=True&blnArtist=True&page=1&keyid=13767315&ShowNbr=0&ShowSeqNbr=0&querytype=WorkID|publisher=BMI|accessdate=February 5, 2012|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6JMXEi9r3?url=http://repertoire.bmi.com/title.asp?blnWriter=True|archive-date=September 3, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> The song is about a woman who begs her lover not to \"leave [her] broken hearted tonight.\"<ref name=\"Karmin Unleashes New Single\">{{cite web|title=Karmin unleashes new single 'Broken Hearted' in time for their Saturday Night Live performance|url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2012/01/30/karmin-new-single-broken-hearted-saturday-night-live/|work=|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> The single debuted at number 84 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Karmin Debuts Video for Brokenhearted|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/chartbeat/499377/karmin-debuts-video-for-makes-chart-gains-with-brokenhearted|work=Billboard|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=April 2, 2012}}</ref> and peaked at number 16 on the chart in its twelfth week.\nInternationally, the song became Karmin's biggest hit single to date, peaking within the top ten of the charts in Australia, New Zealand and the United Kingdom.\n\n==Background and composition==\n\"Brokenhearted\" was written by [[Karmin|Amy Heidemann]], [[Karmin|Nick Noonan]], [[Claude Kelly]], [[Benny Blanco]], [[Emily Wright (songwriter)|Emily Wright]], Henry Walter, [[John Hill (producer)|John Hill]] and Richard Head, produced by Benny Blanco, [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]], Emily Wright, and recorded in late summer of 2011. The single leaked on January 27, prompting the duo to upload it to their YouTube account on January 30. The single was made available for digital download on February 2, with it officially being released to radio on February 7.\n\nIn an interview with ''Entertainment Weekly'', the song's co-writer, Claude Kelly, expressed the goals for the recording, which was one of eight tracks the pair worked on together: \"I had the melody down, and I kept feeling I wanted a song that had the vibe of \u2018[[Fantasy (Mariah Carey song)|Fantasy]]\u2019 by [[Mariah Carey]],\" Kelly explained. \"There hasn\u2019t been a song like that in a million years, one that\u2019s fun and you want to dance to it at a party but it\u2019s not so serious that you can\u2019t have a good time. And Amy can sing her ass off, so I knew she could do it.\"<ref name=\"Karmin Get Ready for 'SNL', Preview Their New Album\">{{cite web|title=Karmin Get Ready for 'SNL', Preview Their New Album|url=http://music-mix.ew.com/2012/02/11/karmin-snl-new-album/|work=EW|publisher=Kyle Anderson|accessdate=March 30, 2012}}</ref> It was also mentioned that the song was inspired by Brandy's [[Brokenhearted (Brandy song)|Brokenhearted]], released in 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=e4-GpLvrEB4|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the digital sheet music published at musicnotes.com by [[EMI Music Publishing]], \"Brokenhearted\" is written in the key of [[E major]] with a tempo of 118 [[beats per minute]].<ref name=\"sheet\">{{cite web|url=|title=Digital Sheet Music \u2013 Karmin - Brokenhearted|publisher=MusicNotes.com. [[EMI Music Publishing]]}}</ref> Heidemann's vocal range in the song spans from the low note of [[G\u266f (musical note)|G\u266f<sub>3</sub>]] to the high note of [[C\u266f (musical note)|C\u266f<sub>5</sub>]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musicnotes.com/sheetmusic/mtd.asp?ppn=MN0105093|title=Brokenhearted|date=June 18, 2012|website=Musicnotes.com}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n\"Brokenhearted\" was well received from critics who complimented Heidemann's vocal prowess and the production's energetic vibe. ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' noted that despite its somber title, it \"certainly has a lot of pep.\"<ref name=\"Karmin's Amy Heidemann and Nick Noonan Release 'Broken Hearted'\">{{cite news|title=Karmin's Amy Heidemann and Nick Noonan Release 'Broken Hearted' In Time For 'SNL' Performance |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/01/31/karmin-broken-hearted-snl_n_1243842.html|work=|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=February 4, 2012|first=Leigh|last=Weingus|date=January 31, 2012}}</ref> Grady Smith of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' calls it a \"sunny pop track... which features another dose of Amy\u2019s trademark rapping over a [[Dr. Luke]]-esque beat.\"<ref name=\"Karmin Unleashes New Single\" /> Andrew Unterberger from Popdust says, \"Last year\u2019s \"[[Crash Your Party]]\" was a good start, but \"Broken Hearted\" faces a much better chance of breaking them through to the Top 40, with a [[Katy Perry]]/Dr. Luke style super-pop groove, the first few notes are all but guaranteed to give you \"[[Last Friday Night (T.G.I.F.)|Last Friday Night]]\" flashbacks and a chorus sentiment (\"Don\u2019t you leave me brokenhearted tonight\") that has definite lovelorn-party-anthem potential.\"<ref name=\"Don't You Leave Karmin 'Broken Hearted' Tonight\">{{cite web|title=Don't You Leave Karmin 'Broken Hearted' Tonight|url=http://popdust.com/2012/01/30/karmin-broken-hearted-new-song-leak/|work=|publisher=Popdust|accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> [[MTV]]'s Liz Barker says it may be \"the sunniest song to ever bear a title like 'Broken Hearted,'\" with a \"super-slick flow that Amy shows off.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=New Song: Karmin, \"Broken Hearted|url=http://buzzworthy.mtv.com/2012/01/30/karmin-broken-hearted/|work=|publisher=MTV|accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Music video==\n\n===Background===\n[[File:Brokenhearted-screenshot.jpg|thumb|right|Heidemann and Noonan in a dramatized version of their true story.]]\nOn February 4, 2012, the group revealed via [[Twitter]] that they were in the pre-production phase for an accompanying [[music video]]. Filming began on February 6, on location in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]],<ref>{{cite web|title=On Location Vacations|url=http://www.onlocationvacations.com/2012/02/05/monday-feb-6-filming-locations-in-los-angeles-new-orleans-new-york-more-including-revenge-now-you-see-me-inside-llewyn-davis-the-corrections/|work=|publisher=On Location Vacations|accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> with additional footage filmed in mid-March. The video was choreographed by [[Richard Jackson (choreographer)|Richard Jackson]], best known for working with [[Lady Gaga]].\n\nThe video is said to be loosely based on how the duo met. It takes place in Amy's apartment, with her thinking back to the night before. Group member Nick Noonan describes it as \"She ran into a guy, who is me. She got along really well, didn\u2019t expect to get along with somebody like that, then at the end of the night they exchanged numbers. The whole song is \u2018Why didn\u2019t you call me? Don\u2019t leave me brokenhearted.\u2019 She's never really felt like this, she's confused, she's anxious. You think this guy might be a jerk, but then at the very end you figure out why he didn't call.\"<ref name=\"Karmin talks SNL, covers, Hello, Brokenhearted\">{{cite web|title=Karmin talks SNL, covers, Hello, Brokenhearted|url=http://www.beatweek.com/music/musicianinterviews/12619-karmin-talks-snl-covers-hello-brokenhearted-the-beatweek-interview/|work=Beatweek|publisher=Beatweek Magazine|accessdate=February 8, 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130102101449/http://www.beatweek.com/music/musicianinterviews/12619-karmin-talks-snl-covers-hello-brokenhearted-the-beatweek-interview/|archivedate=January 2, 2013}}</ref> The 'cheerio' part in the song came about when [[Claude Kelly]] wanted to add a little personality to the song: he asked Amy, what would she say if she was pacing around her apartment waiting for a guy to call you, she said 'Cheerio' and \"it just stuck!\"<ref>[http://www.capitalfm.com/on-air/james-barr/james-show-blog/karmin-and-james-barr/ Capital FM Radio: Playlist, Schedule, Shows, Presenters<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n===Synopsis===\nThe video was directed by [[Marc Klasfeld]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://blog.thenext2shine.com/music-video-karmin-brokenhearted|title=Music Video: Karmin - Brokenhearted - TheNext2Shine.com Emerging Undiscovered Music Talent<!-- Bot generated title -->}}</ref> The video was released on [[Vevo]] on March 22, 2012, with a cameo appearance by [[Hugh Jackman]].<ref name=youtube|>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s8cbak34DR0|title=Karmin - Brokenhearted|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref> The story shifts back and forth between the previous day and the present day. The video starts out with Amy entering the studio late as the band is already in mid-rehearsal, and her bandmates give her concerned looks as to why she seems so out of it, while Amy starts shedding her outdoor garbs to loosen up. She sits down on her bed and trades her discomforting heels for the comfort of throw rugs under her bare feet, grabbing hold of her mic stand and flashing her band a reassuring gesture. They begin to perform \"Brokenhearted\". The night before, Amy, Nick, their band members and other friends party in an apartment, complete with drinking, dancing, a game of darts and [[table tennis]]. Amy thinks she and Nick have a romantic connection. The next morning, Amy furiously checks her phone to see if Nick has called, but he hasn't. At the end of band rehearsals, it turns out that Nick is already seeing someone else.\n\n==Live performances==\nThe band debuted their live televised performance on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]'' on February 11, 2012.<ref name=\"Karmin Unleashes New Single\" /><ref name=\"Karmin's Amy Heidemann and Nick Noonan Release 'Broken Hearted'\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Channing Tatum, Zooey Deschanel to host 'Saturday Night Live' in February|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2012/01/11/channing-tatum-zooey-deschanel-to-host-saturday-night-live-in-february/116119/|work=|publisher=TVbytheNumbers|accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> The band continued a promotional push for the single by appearing and performing the song on [[VH1]] Big Morning Buzz Live, and also announcing that the release date for the album was set for May 8, 2012. In May 2015, they performed the song on [[2nd Indonesian Choice Awards]].\n\n==Credits and personnel==\n*[[Vocals]] - [[Karmin]]\n*[[Songwriting]] - Karmin, [[John Hill (producer)|John Hill]], [[Claude Kelly]], [[Benny Blanco]], Henry Walter, [[Emily Wright (songwriter)|Emily Wright]], Richard Head\n*[[Music production|Production]] - Benny Blanco, [[Cirkut (record producer)|Cirkut]], Emily Wright\n\nCredits adapted from ''Hello'' album liner notes.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|others=[[Karmin]]|title=[[Hello (Karmin EP)|Hello]]|year=2012|type=liner notes|publisher=[[Epic Records]]}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{col-begin}}\n;Digital download<ref>{{cite web |url= https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/hello/id517705569|title=Hello|publisher= [[iTunes]]|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref>\n# \"Brokenhearted\" \u2013 3:47\n\n;Digital remixes<ref>{{cite web |url= https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/brokenhearted-remixes/id533215016|title=Brokenhearted Digital Remixes|publisher= iTunes|accessdate=June 12, 2012}}</ref>\n# \"Brokenhearted (R3hab Remix Extended)\" \u2013 4:46\n# \"Brokenhearted (Mixin Marc & Tony Svejda Club Remix)\" \u2013 5:36\n# \"Brokenhearted (Mixin Marc & Tony Svejda Radio Mix)\" \u2013 3:56\n# \"Brokenhearted (Mixin Marc & Tony Svejda Poppin' Bottles Remix)\" \u2013 6:27\n# \"Brokenhearted (Razor N Guido Main Mix)\" \u2013 7:40\n# \"Brokenhearted (Razor N Guido Mixshow)\" \u2013 5:39\n# \"Brokenhearted (Razor N Guido Radio Edit)\" \u2013 4:03\n# \"Brokenhearted (Razor N Guido Dub)\" \u2013 4:03\n# \"Brokenhearted (RNG DuHb)\" \u2013 7:10\n\n;UK Digital EP<ref>{{cite web |url= https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/brokenhearted-remixes-ep/id530114396?ign-mpt=uo%3D2|title=Brokenhearted (Remixes) - EP|publisher= iTunes|accessdate=July 28, 2012}}</ref>\n# \"Brokenhearted\" \u2013 3:47\n# \"Brokenhearted (R3hab Remix Edit)\" \u2013 3:25\n# \"Brokenhearted (Mixin Marc & Tony Svejda Radio Mix)\" \u2013 3:56\n# \"Brokenhearted (RNG Dub)\" \u2013 7:10\n\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Chart (2012)\n!Peak<br