{"title_page": "Administrator of the Northern Territory", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=September 2010}}\n{{Infobox official post\n| post                     = Administrator\n| body                     = the Northern Territory\n| native_name              = \n| flag                     = \n| flagsize                 = \n| flagborder               = \n| flagcaption              = \n| insignia                 = Coat of Arms of Australia.svg\n| insigniasize             = \n| insigniacaption          = \n| image                    = \n| imagesize                = \n| alt                      = \n| incumbent                = [[Vicki O'Halloran]]\n| incumbentsince           = 31 October 2017\n| type                     = \n| status                   = \n| department               = Office of the Administrator\n| style                    = [[The Honourable]]\n| member_of                = \n| reports_to               = \n| residence                = [[Government House, Darwin]]\n| seat                     = [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]], [[Northern Territory]]\n| nominator                = \n| appointer                = [[Governor-General of Australia]]\n| appointer_qualified      = \n| termlength               = \n| termlength_qualified     = \n| constituting_instrument  = \n| precursor                = \n| formation                = \n| first                    = [[John A. Gilruth]]\n| last                     = \n| abolished                = \n| succession               = \n| abbreviation             = \n| unofficial_names         = \n| deputy                   = Deputy Administrator Pat Miller \n| salary                   = \n| website                  = [https://govhouse.nt.gov.au/ Administrator of the Northern Territory]\n}}\nThe '''Administrator of the Northern Territory''' is an official appointed by the [[Governor-General of Australia]] to represent the government of the Commonwealth in the [[Northern Territory]].  He or she performs functions similar to those of a [[Governors of the Australian states|state governor]].\n\nStrictly speaking, the appointment of an Administrator is made by the Governor-General-in-Council, that is, the Governor-General acting on the ''advice'' of the [[Federal Executive Council (Australia)|Commonwealth Government]], rather than the advice of the [[Government of the Northern Territory]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Northern Territory (Self-Government) Act 1978 - SECT 32 Office of Administrator |url=http://www6.austlii.edu.au/cgi-bin/viewdoc/au/legis/cth/consol_act/nta1978425/s32.html |publisher=Australian Government |accessdate=22 May 2019|via=[[Austlii]] }}</ref>  The Northern Territory received self-government on 1 July 1978, in accordance with the provisions of the ''[[Northern Territory (Self-Government) Act 1978]] ([[Australian Parliament|Cth]])''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Northern Territory (Self-Government) Act 1978|url=http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/legis/cth/consol_act/nta1978425/}}</ref>  Since then, the practice has arisen that in making an appointment the Governor-General-in-Council will act on the ''recommendation'' of the Northern Territory Government.\n\nUnlike an Australian [[Governors of the Australian states|State Governor]], the Administrator is not the ''direct'' representative of the [[Monarchy of Australia|Queen]] in the Territory but is instead appointed by the Queen's representative in the Commonwealth, the Governor-General, to administer the Territory in accordance with the Act. In practice, however, the Administrator performs a similar constitutional role to that of a state governor and can be considered the Queen's ''indirect'' representative in the Territory.\n\nThe Administrator formally appoints the [[Chief Minister of the Northern Territory]] and the members of the Cabinet after every election.  In all but a few cases, he or she is required by convention to act on the Cabinet's advice.  The Administrator gives [[royal assent]] to all bills passed by the [[Northern Territory Legislative Assembly]].  Although the Governor-General (in practice, the Commonwealth Government) has the power to veto any territorial bill, in practice this right is almost never exercised.\n\nThe office of the ''Deputy of the Administrator'' was created in 1997.\n\nIn 2014, the Governor-General granted current, future and living former Administrators the title of 'The Honourable' for life,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Baker |first1=Karen |title=Title Honourable for Administrators of the Northern Territory |url=https://www.legislation.gov.au/Details/C2014G01261 |website=Federal Register of Legislation |publisher=Australian Government |accessdate=22 May 2019 |date=30 July 2014}}</ref> following the lead of Governors-General and Governors of New South Wales in granting the title.{{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n\nThe present Administrator is [[Vicki O'Halloran]], [[Order of Australia|AO]].<ref>[http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/ NT Office of Administrator] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040404010528/http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/ |date=2004-04-04 }}</ref>\n\n== South Australia (1863 to 1912) ==\nOn 6 July 1863, land now known as the Northern Territory was annexed to the [[Colony of South Australia]].  Legislation regulating the sale of land in the Northern Territory which  was given assent on 12 November 1863 included provision for both the appointment of a [[Government Resident]] and a description of the powers of this office.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Northern Territory Act 1863 No. 23 |url=https://dspace.flinders.edu.au/xmlui/bitstream/handle/2328/2526/231863.pdf?sequence=1&isAllowed=y |publisher=Government of South Australia |accessdate=18 May 2019 |pages=275 and 278-279 |date=12 November 1863 |quote=appoint an officer to be resident in the said territory, to be called the Government Resident, and all other necessary and proper officers for securing the order. and good government of the said territory}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=\"10%\"| No.\n! width=\"50%\"| Government Resident\n! width=\"20%\"| From\n! width=\"20%\"| To\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Boyle Travers Finniss|The Hon. Boyle Travers Finniss]]\n| 3 March 1864<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ayers |first1=Henry |title=Untitled announcement of the appointment of the Government Resident of the Northern Territory |url=http://www8.austlii.edu.au/au/other/sa_gazette/1864/10.pdf |website=The South Australian Government Gazette |publisher=Government of South Australia |accessdate=18 May 2019 |page=184 |date=10 March 1864 |quote=His Excellency has this day been pleased to appoint Boyle Travers Finniss, Esq., to be Government Resident in and for the New Territory recently annexed to this Province by Her Majesty's Royal Letters Patent, bearing date July 6th, 1863}}</ref>\n| 4 November 1865<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1864_finniss.pdf |title=William Bloomfield Douglas |accessdate=2011-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321091050/http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1864_finniss.pdf |archivedate=2011-03-21 |publisher=Northern Territory Government}}</ref>\n|-\n| (acting)\n| [[James Millner (doctor)|James Stokes Millner MD]]\n| January 1870\n| April 1870\n|-\n| 2\n| [[William Bloomfield Douglas]]\n| 27 April 1870\n| June 1873<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1870_douglas.pdf |title=William Bloomfield Douglas |accessdate=2011-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321091040/http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1870_douglas.pdf |archivedate=2011-03-21 |publisher=Northern Territory Government}}</ref>\n|-\n| (acting)\n| [[James Millner (doctor)|James Stokes Millner MD]]\n| June 1873<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article28695825 |title= The Ministry have accepted the resignation ... |newspaper=[[The Advertiser (Adelaide)|The South Australian Advertiser (Adelaide, SA : 1858 - 1889)]] |location=Adelaide, SA |date=9 June 1873 |accessdate=1 May 2012 |page=2 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n| October 1873\n|-\n| 3\n| [[George Byng Scott]]\n| 6 October 1873\n| 30 June 1876<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1873_scott.pdf |title=George Byng Scott |accessdate=2012-02-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120024531/http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1873_scott.pdf |archivedate=2012-01-20 |publisher=Northern Territory Government}}</ref>\n|-\n| 4\n| [[Edward William Price]]\n| 1 July 1876\n| 6 March 1883<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1876_price.pdf |title=Gilbert Rotherdale McMinn |accessdate=2012-03-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211085317/http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1876_price.pdf |archivedate=2012-02-11 |publisher=Northern Territory Government}}</ref>\n|-\n| (acting)\n| [[Gilbert Rotherdale McMinn]]\n| March 1883<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article3153769 |title=Appointment. |newspaper=[[The Northern Territory Times|Northern Territory Times and Gazette (Darwin, NT : 1873 - 1927)]] |location=Darwin, NT |date=31 March 1883 |accessdate=1 May 2012 |page=1 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n| March 1884\n|-\n| 5\n| [[John Langdon Parsons|John Parsons]]\n| 19 March 1884\n| 14 February 1890<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1884_parsons.pdf |title=John Langdon Parsons |accessdate=2011-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321091001/http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1884_parsons.pdf |archivedate=2011-03-21 |publisher=Northern Territory Government}}</ref>\n|-\n| 6\n| [[John George Knight|John Knight FRIBA]]\n| 16 July 1890\n| 10 January 1892<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1890_knight.pdf |title=John George Knight |accessdate=2011-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110321090949/http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1890_knight.pdf |archivedate=2011-03-21 |publisher=Northern Territory Government}}</ref>\n|-\n| 7\n| [[Charles Dashwood (judge)|Charles James Dashwood]]\n| 24 February 1892\n| 31 January 1905<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1892_dashwood.pdf |title=Charles James Dashwood |accessdate=2012-02-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120094920/http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1892_dashwood.pdf |archivedate=2012-01-20  |publisher=Northern Territory Government}}</ref>\n|-\n| 8\n| [[Charles Edward Herbert]]\n| 1 February 1905\n| 8 February 1910<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1905_herbert.pdf |title=Charles Edward Herbert |accessdate=2011-05-16 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110402193139/http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1905_herbert.pdf |archivedate=2011-04-02 |publisher=Northern Territory Government}}</ref>\n|-\n| 9\n| [[Samuel James Mitchell|The Hon. Samuel Mitchell]]\n| 1 April 1910\n| 25 March 1912\n|}\n\n== Commonwealth of Australia (1912 to present) ==\n\nAdministrators and Government Residents of the [[Northern Territory]]\nafter transfer of control to the Commonwealth Government:\n\n=== Administrator (1912 to 1919) ===\n\n[[Image:John Gilruth 1.jpg|thumb|From left: [[Minister for Foreign Affairs (Australia)|Minister]] [[Josiah Thomas]], [[Sir Walter Balfour Barttelot|Sir Walter Barttelot]] and Administrator [[John A. Gilruth|John Gilruth]] in 1912.]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=\"10%\"| No.\n! width=\"50%\"| Administrator\n! width=\"20%\"| From\n! width=\"20%\"| To\n|-\n| 1\n| [[John A. Gilruth|John Gilruth FRSE MRCVS]]\n| 25 March 1912\n| 1 August 1919\n|}\n\n=== Director (1919 to 1921) ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=\"10%\"| No.\n! width=\"50%\"| Director\n! width=\"20%\"| From\n! width=\"20%\"| To\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Henry Carey (Australia)|Henry Ernest Carey]]\n| 1 August 1919\n| 17 January 1921\n|}\n\n=== Administrator (1921 to 1927) ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=\"10%\"| No.\n! width=\"50%\"| Administrator\n! width=\"20%\"| From\n! width=\"20%\"| To\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Frederic Urquhart]]\n| 17 January 1921\n| 1 March 1927\n|}\n\n=== Government Resident (1927 to 1931) ===\n\nFrom 1926 to 1931, the [[Northern Territory]] was divided into the territories of [[Central Australia (territory)|Central Australia]] and [[North Australia (territory)|North Australia]], with the border at the [[20th parallel south]]. Each territory was administered by a  Government Resident located respectively in [[Alice Springs]] (then known as Stuart) and in [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]]. \nBoth territories were reincorporated as the Northern Territory in 1931.<ref name=\"ling\">{{cite web |last1=Ling |first1=Ted |title=Dividing the Territory, 1926\u201331 |url=http://guides.naa.gov.au/records-about-northern-territory/part1/chapter3/3.3.aspx |website=Commonwealth Government Records about the Northern Territory |publisher=National Archives of Australia |accessdate=28 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Biography: Previous Incumbents - Victor George Carrington|publisher=Government House Northern Territory Government|url=http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1926_cawood_1929_carrington.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=2 April 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110402193043/http://www.nt.gov.au/administrator/pdf/cv/1926_cawood_1929_carrington.pdf|archivedate=2 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=\"10%\"| No.\n! width=\"50%\"| Government Resident ([[North Australia (territory)|North Australia]])\n! width=\"20%\"| From\n! width=\"20%\"| To\n|-\n| 1\n| [[Robert Weddell]]\n| 1 March 1927\n| 12 June 1931\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! width=\"10%\"| No.\n! width=\"50%\"| Government Resident ([[Central Australia (territory)|Central Australia]])\n! width=\"20%\"| From\n! width=\"20%\"| To\n|-\n| 1\n| [[John Charles Cawood|