s_religion_id=0&affiliations_year=2010|title=Religions in Northern Mariana Islands {{!}} PEW-GRF|website=www.globalreligiousfutures.org|access-date=2019-08-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalreligiousfutures.org/countries/guam#/?affiliations_religion_id=0&affiliations_year=2010|title=Religions in Guam {{!}} PEW-GRF|website=www.globalreligiousfutures.org|access-date=2019-08-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.globalreligiousfutures.org/countries/puerto-rico#/?affiliations_religion_id=0&affiliations_year=2010|title=Religions in Puerto Rico {{!}} PEW-GRF|website=www.globalreligiousfutures.org|access-date=2019-08-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://globalreligiousfutures.org/countries/u-s-virgin-islands#/?affiliations_religion_id=0&affiliations_year=2010|title=Religions in U S Virgin Islands {{!}} PEW-GRF|website=globalreligiousfutures.org|access-date=2019-08-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2017/03/29/key-findings-about-puerto-rico/|title=Key findings about Puerto Rico|date=March 29, 2017|website=Pew Research Center|access-date=August 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pewforum.org/2014/11/13/religion-in-latin-america/#religious-affiliations-of-latin-americans-and-u-s-hispanics|title=Religion in Latin America|date=November 13, 2014|website=Pew Research Center|access-date=August 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewforum.org/2011/12/19/table-christian-population-as-percentages-of-total-population-by-country/|title=Table: Christian Population as Percentages of Total Population by Country|date=December 19, 2011|website=Pew Research Center|access-date=August 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \"\n! Territory !! Percent<br /> Christian !! Percent<br />all religions \n|-\n| {{flag|American Samoa}} || 98.3% || 99.3%\n|-\n| {{flag|Northern Mariana Islands}} ||  81.3% || 99%\n|-\n| {{flag|Guam}} || 94.2% || 98.3%\n|-\n| {{flag|Puerto Rico}} || 89% || 98.1%\n|-\n| {{flag|US Virgin Islands}} || 94.8% || 96.3%\n|}\n\n=== 2018 ISPU Poll ===\n\n==== Highlights ====\nIn 2018 The Institute for Social Policy and Understanding published an important study that examined the sentiments of various american faith populations on a variety of issues, focused primarily around ideas of violent extremism, religious pluralism and islamophobia. Their results found that majority of americans, across faith groups, do hold balanced views on Islam and Muslims, and also highlighted the shared sentiments of Muslim and Jewish communities on many of the questions, and the gaps identified between the Evangelical Christians polled and the other members of the study.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ispu.org/american-muslim-poll-2018-full-report/|title=American Muslim Poll 2018: Full Report {{!}} ISPU|date=2018-04-30|website=Institute for Social Policy and Understanding|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-25}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Islamophobia Index<ref name=\":3\" />\n!Most Muslims living in the United States... (% Net agree shown)\n!Muslim\n!Jewish\n!Catholic\n!Protestant\n!White Evangelical\n!Non-Affiliated\n!General Public\n|-\n|Are more prone to violence\n|18%\n|15%\n|12%\n|13%\n|23%\n|8%\n|13%\n|-\n|Discriminate against women\n|12%\n|23%\n|29%\n|30%\n|36%\n|18%\n|26%\n|-\n|Are hostile to the United States\n|12%\n|13%\n|9%\n|14%\n|23%\n|8%\n|12%\n|-\n|Are less civilized than other people\n|8%\n|6%\n|4%\n|6%\n|10%\n|1%\n|6%\n|-\n|Are partially responsible for acts of violence carried out by other Muslims\n|10%\n|16%\n|11%\n|12%\n|14%\n|8%\n|12%\n|-\n|Index (0 min - 100 max)\n|17\n|22\n|22\n|31\n|40\n|14\n|24\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Pride Index<ref name=\":3\" />\n!My faith identity/ community... (% Net agree shown)\n!Muslim\n!Jewish\n!Catholic\n!Protestant\n!White Evangelical\n!Non-Affiliated\n!General Public\n|-\n|Is a source of happiness\n|85%\n|72%\n|73%\n|81%\n|94%\n|34%\n|68%\n|-\n|Contributes to society\n|85%\n|91%\n|78%\n|79%\n|95%\n|44%\n|71%\n|-\n|Makes me proud\n|86%\n|87%\n|85%\n|83%\n|95%\n|37%\n|72%\n|-\n|Index\n|87\n|86\n|82\n|85\n|93\n|58\n|78\n|}\n\nThe following graph shows data across six different faith populations in the United States, and their answers to the two questions below. (Note: \"W. Evang.\" is short for White Evangelical, the specific demographic surveyed.):\n\n'''Question 1:''' Some people think that for the military to target and kill civilians is sometimes justified, while others think that this kind of violence is never justified. Which is your opinion?\n\n'''Question 2:''' Some people think that for an individual or a small group of people to target and kill civilians is sometimes justified, while others think that this kind of violence is never justified. Which is your opinion?\n<br />{{ #invoke:Chart | bar chart\n| group 1 = 71 : 51 : 35 : 34 : 23 : 55\n| group 2 = 80 : 78 : 76 : 68 : 62 : 80\n| colors = green : yellow\n| group names = Question 1 (% Never Justified) : Question 2 (% Never Justified)\n| x legends = Muslim : Jewish : Catholic : Protestant : W. Evang. : Non-Affiliated\n}}\n\nThe following graph contains additional data collected by ISPU during their 2018 poll. The following statements were posed to participants and they were asked to answer on a scale from strongly agree to strongly disagree. The chart below shows the total percentage from each American faith demographic that agreed with the statements below. (Note: \"W. Evang.\" is short for White Evangelical, the specific demographic surveyed.)\n\n'''Question 1:''' I want to live in a country where no one is targeted for their religious idenitity\n\n'''Question 2:''' The negative things politicians say regarding Muslims is harmful to our country\n\n'''Question 3:''' Most Muslims living in the United States are committed to the wellbeing of America\n\n'''Question 4:''' Most people associate negative stereotypes with my faith identity\n<br />{{ #invoke:Chart | bar chart\n| group 1 = 91 : 95 : 85 : 88 : 78 : 88\n| group 2 = 78 : 69 : 61 : 61 : 45 : 78\n| group 3 = 81 : 66 : 64 : 50 : 36 : 65\n| group 4 = 62 : 46 : 27 : 24 : 34 : 28\n| colors = blue : orange : purple : green\n| group names = Question 1 (% Net agree) : Question 2 (% Net agree) : Question 3 (% Net Agree) : Question 4 (% Net agree)\n| x legends = Muslim : Jewish : Catholic : Protestant : W. Evang. : Non-Affiliated\n}}\n\n==Religion and politics==\n{{Main|Religion and politics in the United States}}\n{{See also|Religious affiliations of Presidents of the United States|Religious affiliation in the United States Senate}}\n\n[[File:Civil marriage is a civil right.JPG|thumb|right|The U.S. guarantees [[freedom of religion]], and some churches in the U.S. take strong stances on political subjects.]]\n\nIn August 2010, 67% of Americans said religion was losing influence, compared with 59% who said this in 2006. Majorities of white evangelical Protestants (79%), white mainline Protestants (67%), black Protestants (56%), Catholics (71%), and the religiously unaffiliated (62%) all agreed that religion was losing influence on American life; 53% of the total public said this was a bad thing, while just 10% see it as a good thing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pewresearch.org/databank/dailynumber/?NumberID=1079|publisher=Pew Forum on Religion & Public Life|title=Religion Losing Influence in America|access-date=September 16, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920003855/http://pewresearch.org/databank/dailynumber/?NumberID=1079|archive-date=September 20, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nPoliticians frequently discuss their religion when campaigning, and [[fundamentalist Christianity|fundamentalists]] and black Protestants are highly politically active. However, to keep their status as [[tax-exempt organization]]s they must not officially endorse a candidate. Historically Catholics were heavily [[History of the United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] before the 1970s, while mainline Protestants comprised the core of the [[History of the United States Republican Party|Republican Party]]. Those patterns have faded away\u2014Catholics, for example, now split about 50\u201350. However, white evangelicals since 1980 have made up a solidly Republican group that favors conservative candidates. Secular voters are increasingly Democratic.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://pewforum.org/docs/?DocID=174 |title=Religion and the 2006 Elections |publisher=Pew Forum |date=2006-12-01 |accessdate=2012-03-17}}</ref>\n\nOnly three presidential candidates for major parties have been Catholics, all for the Democratic party:\n* [[Alfred E. Smith]] in [[1928 United States presidential election|presidential election of 1928]] was subjected to anti-Catholic rhetoric, which seriously hurt him in the Baptist areas of the South and Lutheran areas of the Midwest, but he did well in the Catholic urban strongholds of the Northeast.\n* [[John F. Kennedy]] secured the Democratic presidential nomination in 1960. In the [[1960 United States presidential election|1960 election]], Kennedy faced accusations that as a Catholic president he would do as the Pope would tell him to do, a charge that Kennedy refuted in a famous address to Protestant ministers.\n* [[John Kerry]], a Catholic, won the Democratic presidential nomination in 2004. In the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 election]] religion was hardly an issue, and most Catholics voted for his Protestant opponent [[George W. Bush]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/5297138 |title=Exit poll - Decision 2004- NBCNews.com |publisher=NBC News |date= |accessdate=2012-12-29}}</ref>\n\n[[Joe Biden]] is the first Catholic vice president.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/politicaljunkie/2009/01/the_first_catholic_vice_presid.html|title=The First Catholic Vice President?|date=9 January 2009|work=NPR.org|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Joe Lieberman]] was the first major presidential candidate that was Jewish, on the [[Al Gore|Gore]]\u2013Lieberman [[2000 United States presidential election|campaign of 2000]] (although [[John Kerry]] and [[Barry Goldwater]] both had Jewish ancestry, they were practicing Christians). [[Bernie Sanders]] ran against [[Hillary Clinton]] in the Democratic primary of 2016. He was the first major Jewish candidate to compete in the presidential primary process. However, Sanders noted during the campaign that he does not actively practice any religion.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/bernie-sanders-finally-answers-the-god-question/2016/01/26/83429390-bfb0-11e5-bcda-62a36b394160_story.html|title=Why Bernie Sanders doesn't participate in organized religion|date=27 January 2016|work=www.washingtonpost.com|accessdate=4 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 [[Keith Ellison]] of [[Minnesota]] became the first Muslim elected to Congress; when [[Quran oath controversy of the 110th United States Congress|re-enacting his swearing-in for photos]], he used the copy of the [[Qur'an]] once owned by Thomas Jefferson.<ref>Michael Isikoff, \"I'm a Sunni Muslim\", [http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/16474497/site/newsweek/page/0/ ''Newsweek'' Jan. 4, 2007]{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> [[Andr\u00e9 Carson]] is the second Muslim to serve in Congress.\n\nA Gallup poll released in 2007<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.gallup.com/poll/26611/Some-Americans-Reluctant-Vote-Mormon-72YearOld-Presidential-Candidates.aspx |title= Some Americans Reluctant to Vote for Mormon, 72-Year-Old Presidential Candidates. Strong support for black, women, Catholic candidates |publisher= Gallup News Service |author= Jeffrey M. Jones |accessdate= 2007-12-25 |date= 2007-02-20}}</ref> indicated that 53% of Americans would refuse to vote for an [[atheist]] as president, up from 48% in 1987 and 1999. But then the number started to drop again and reached record low 43% in 2012 and 40% in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.gallup.com/poll/155285/atheists-muslims-bias-presidential-candidates.aspx |title= Atheists, Muslims See Most Bias as Presidential Candidates |publisher= Gallup News Service |author = Jeffrey M. Jones |accessdate= 2017-03-26 |date= 2012-06-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gallup.com/poll/183713/socialist-presidential-candidates-least-appealing.aspx |title= In U.S., Socialist Presidential Candidates Least Appealing |publisher= Gallup News Service |author = Justin Mccarthy |accessdate= 2017-03-26 |date= 2015-06-22}}</ref>\n\n[[Mitt Romney]], the Republican presidential nominee in 2012, is [[Mormon]] and a member of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]]. He is the former governor of the state of [[Massachusetts]], and his father [[George W. Romney|George Romney]] was the governor of the state of [[Michigan]]. The Romneys were involved in Mormonism in their states and in the state of [[Utah]].\n\nOn January 3, 2013, [[Tulsi Gabbard]] became the first [[Hindu]] member of Congress, using a copy of the [[Bhagavad Gita]] while swearing-in.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kaleem|first1=Jaweed|title=Tulsi Gabbard, First Hindu In Congress, Uses Bhagavad Gita At Swearing-In|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/01/04/tulsi-gabbard-hindu-bhagavad-gita-swearing-in_n_2410078.html|work=HuffPost|accessdate=October 17, 2017|date=January 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n== 2010 ARDA data ==\n\nThe [[Association of Religion Data Archives]] (ARDA) surveyed congregations for their memberships. Churches were asked for their membership numbers. Adjustments were made for those congregations that did not respond and for religious groups that reported only adult membership.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.thearda.com/mapsReports/rcms_notes.asp |title= ARDA Sources for Religious Congregations & Membership Data |publisher= [[Association of Religion Data Archives|ARDA]] |year= 2000 |accessdate= 2010-05-29}}</ref> ARDA estimates that most of the churches not responding were black Protestant congregations. Significant difference in results from other databases include the lower representation of adherents of 1) all kinds (62.7%), 2) Christians (59.9%), 3) Protestants (less than 36%); and the greater number of unaffiliated (37.3%).\n\n[[File:Highest percentage against the religious national average in the United States.svg|thumb|350px|Percentage of religion against average, 2001\n\n{|\n| Major\n| &gt;10%\n| &gt;20%\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #FF6E6E;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #FF0000;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #AD0000;\" |\n| Catholic\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #FFC34A;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #FFAA00;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #B27700;\" |\n| Baptist\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #7AFF7A;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #00FF00;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #009800;\" |\n| Lutheran\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #6BFFE7;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #00FFD5;\" |\n|\n| Methodist\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #BEBEBE;\" |\n|\n| \n| No religion\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #7195FF;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #0040FF;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #0029A4;\" |\n| Mormonism\n|-\n|\n|\n| style=\"background-color: #5F0092;\" |\n| Protestant\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #B397CA;\" |\n|\n|\n| Pentecostal\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #FFDE11;\" |\n|\n|\n| Christian <small>''(unspecified/other)''</small>\n|}\n]]\n\n[[File:Percent Religious in the United States per State 2014.svg|thumb|350px|Percentage of state populations that identify with a religion rather than \"no religion\", 2014\n{{legend|#000741|85-90%}}\n{{legend|#000B6D|80-85%}}  \n{{legend|#031296|75-80%}} \n{{legend|#0115C3|70-75%}}   \n{{legend|#001BFF|65-70%}}   \n{{legend|#2F45FF|60-65%}}  \n]]\n\n[[File:Map of US, Religions.svg|thumb|350px|Plurality of religious preference by state, 2001. Data are unavailable for [[Alaska]] and [[Hawaii]].\n\n{|\n| &lt;30%\n| &lt;40%\n| &lt;50%\n| &gt;50%\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #33ccff;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #0096ff;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #0000ff;\" |\n|\n| Catholic\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #ff5eff;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #ff0099;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #ff0000;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #be0303;\" |\n| Baptist\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #ffcc33;\" |\n|\n|\n|\n| Methodist\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #ffffcc;\" |\n| style=\"background-color: #ffff99;\" |\n|\n|\n| Lutheran\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"background-color: #009900;\" |\n| Mormon\n|-\n| style=\"background-color: #c0c0c0;\" |\n|\n|\n|\n| No religion\n|}\n\n]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|+ align=top | Religious groups\n|-\n! align=left | Religious group !! Number<br />in year<br />2010 !! % in<br />year<br />2010\n|-\n| align=left | Total US pop year 2010 || 308,745,538 || 100.0%\n|-\n| align=left | Evangelical Protestant || 50,013,107 || 16.2%\n|-\n| align=left | Mainline Protestant || 22,568,258 || 7.3%\n|-\n| align=left | Black Protestant || 4,877,067 || 1.6%\n|-\n| align=left | ''Protestant total'' || 77,458,432 || 25.1%\n|-\n| align=left | Catholic || 58,934,906 || 19.1%\n|-\n| align=left | Orthodox || 1,056,535 || 0.3%\n|-\n| align=left | adherents (unadjusted) || 150,596,792 || 48.8%\n|-\n| align=left | unclaimed || 158,148,746 || 51.2%\n|-\n| align=left | other \u2013 including Mormon & Christ Scientist || 13,146,919 || 4.3%\n|-\n| align=left | The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter Day Saints (Mormon, LDS) || 6,144,582 || 2.0%\n|-\n| align=left | other \u2013 excluding Mormon || 7,002,337 || 2.3%\n|-\n| align=left | Jewish estimate || 6,141,325 || 2.0% <!-- Note: the estimates for Jewish, Buddhist, and Hindu are from 2000. The 2010 version did not offer estimates except for Muslims. -->\n|-\n| align=left | Buddhist estimate || 2,000,000 || 0.7%\n|-\n| align=left | Muslim estimate || 2,600,082 || 0.8%\n|-\n| align=left | Hindu estimate || 400,000 || 0.4%\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| Source: [[Association of Religion Data Archives|ARDA]]<ref name=\"ARDA2000\">{{cite web |url= http://www.thearda.com/mapsReports/reports/US_2000.asp |title= The Association of Religion Data Archives (ARDA), Year 2000 Report |publisher= [[Association of Religion Data Archives|ARDA]] |year= 2000 |accessdate= 2011-06-04 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080321210839/http://www.thearda.com/mapsReports/reports/US_2000.asp |archive-date= March 21, 2008 |url-status= dead }} Churches were asked for their membership numbers. ARDA estimates that most of the churches not reporting were black Protestant congregations.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thearda.com/rcms2010/r/u/rcms2010_99_us_name_2010.asp |title=The Association of Religion Data Archives (ARDA), Year 2010 Report|publisher= [[Association of Religion Data Archives|ARDA]] |year= 2010}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==ARIS findings regarding self-identification==<!---[[American Religious Identification Survey]] redirects here --->\nThe United States government does not collect religious data in its census. The survey below, the [[Institute for the Study of Secularism in Society and Culture#American Religious Identification Survey (ARIS)|American Religious Identification Survey]] (ARIS) of 2008, was a random digit-dialed telephone [[statistical survey|survey]] of 54,461 American residential households in the [[contiguous United States]]. The 1990 sample size was 113,723; 2001 sample size was 50,281.\n\nAdult respondents were asked the [[open-ended question]], \"What is your religion, if any?\" Interviewers did not prompt or offer a suggested list of potential answers. The religion of the spouse or partner was also asked. If the initial answer was \"Protestant\" or \"Christian\" further questions were asked to probe which particular denomination. About one third of the sample was asked more detailed demographic questions.\n\n'''Religious Self-Identification of the U.S. Adult Population: 1990, 2001, 2008'''<ref name=ARIS2008 /><br />Figures are not adjusted for refusals to reply; investigators suspect refusals are possibly more representative of \"no religion\" than any other group.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n|+ align=bottom | '''Source: ARIS 2008'''<ref name=ARIS2008>{{cite web |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/metro/documents/aris030609.pdf | title = American Religious Identification Survey (ARIS) 2008 | author = Barry A. Kosmin and Ariela Keysar | year = 2009 | publisher = Trinity College | location = Hartford, Connecticut, US |accessdate= 2009-04-01}}</ref>\n! Group<br />|| 1990<br />adults<br />x 1,000<br />|| 2001<br />adults<br />x 1,000<br />|| 2008<br />adults<br />x 1,000<br />||<br />Numerical<br />Change<br />1990\u2013<br />2008<br />as %<br />of 1990<br />|| 1990<br />% of<br />adults<br />|| 2001<br />% of<br />adults<br />|| 2008<br />% of<br />adults<br />|| change<br />in % of<br />total<br />adults<br />1990\u2013<br />2008<br />\n|-\n| align=left | Adult population, total || 175,440 || 207,983 || 228,182 || 30.1% || || || ||\n|-\n| align=left | Adult population, responded || 171,409 || 196,683 || 216,367 || 26.2% || 97.7% || 94.6% || 94.8% || \u22122.9%\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" | '''Total Christian''' || 151,225 || 159,514 || 173,402 || 14.7% || 86.2% || 76.7% || 76.0% || \u221210.2%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; text-indent:20px;\"| '''Catholic''' || 46,004 || 50,873 || 57,199 || 24.3% || 26.2% || 24.5% || 25.1% || \u22121.2%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; text-indent:5px;\"| '''non-Catholic Christian''' || 105,221 || 108,641 || 116,203 || 10.4% || 60.0% || 52.2% || 50.9% || \u22129.0%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; text-indent:20px;\"| '''Baptist''' || 33,964 || 33,820 || 36,148 || 6.4% || 19.4% || 16.3% || 15.8% || \u22123.5%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left; text-indent:20px;\"| '''Mainline Christian''' || 32,784 || 35,788 || 29,375 || \u221210.4% || 18.7% || 17.2% || 12.9% || \u22125.8%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align: